in Florida]] [[File:US 441.svg|31px|link=U.S. Route 441 in Florida]]\n| blank4_name_sec2                = [[List of state roads in Florida|State Routes]]\n| blank4_info_sec2                = [[File:Florida's Turnpike shield.svg|27px|link=Florida's Turnpike]] [[File:Florida A1A.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road A1A]] [[File:Florida 814.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 814]] [[File:Florida 816.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 816]] [[File:Florida 817.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 817]] [[File:Florida 818.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 818]] [[File:Florida 820.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 820]] [[File:Florida 822.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 822]] [[File:Florida 823.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 823]] [[File:Florida 824.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 824]] [[File:Florida 842.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 842]] [[File:Florida 845.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 845]] [[File:Florida 848.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 848]] [[File:Florida 852.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 852]] [[File:Florida 858.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 858]] [[File:Florida 869.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 869]] [[File:Florida 870.svg|27px|link=Florida State Road 870]]\n| blank5_name_sec2                =\n| blank5_info_sec2                =\n| blank6_name_sec2                =\n| blank6_info_sec2                =\n| blank7_name_sec2                = [[Commuter Rail]]\n| blank7_info_sec2                = [[Silver Service|Amtrak]], [[Virgin Trains USA]], [[Tri-Rail]]\n| website                         = {{URL|www.broward.org}}\n| official_name                   =\n}}\n\n'''Broward County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in southeastern [[Florida]], US.  According to the 2019 census bureau estimate, the county had a [[population]] of 1,952,778, making it the second-most populous county in the state of Florida and the [[List of the most populous counties in the United States|17th-most populous county in the United States]].<ref name=\"census.gov\"/> The [[county seat]] is [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 31, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBroward County is one of the three counties in [[South Florida]] that make up the [[Miami metropolitan area]], which was home to an estimated 6,198,782 people in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/miamidadecountyflorida,browardcountyflorida,palmbeachcountyflorida/POP060210|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Miami-Dade County, Florida; Broward County, Florida; Palm Beach County, Florida|website=www.census.gov}}</ref>\n\nThe county has 31 municipalities, which consist of 24 [[city (Florida)|incorporated cities]] and many [[unincorporated area]]s. It is also Florida's seventh-largest county in terms of land area, with {{convert|1322.8|sqmi|km2}}. Broward County's urbanized area  occupies 427.8 square miles of land. The largest portion of the county is the Conservation Area that extends west to border [[Collier County]]. The conservation area is 796.9 square miles and consists of wetlands, much of which are part of the [[Everglades National Park]]. At its widest points, the County stretches approximately 50.3 miles east to west and approximately 27.4 miles from north to south, averaging 5 to 25 feet in elevation.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Napoleon Bonaparte Broward.jpg|thumb|Napoleon Bonaparte Broward (1857-1910)|left|164x164px]]\n\n===Native people===\nThe earliest evidence of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] settlement in the Miami region came from about 12,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite book |title=Miami: The Magic City |last=Parks |first=Arva Moore |authorlink= |year=1991 |publisher=Centennial Press |location=Miami|isbn=0-9629402-2-4 |page=12 |url= }}</ref> The first inhabitants settled on the banks of the [[Miami River (Florida)|Miami River]], with the main villages on the northern banks.\n\nThe inhabitants at the time of first European contact were the [[Tequesta]] people, who controlled much of southeastern Florida, including what is now [[Miami-Dade County]], [[Broward County]], and the southern part of [[Palm Beach County]]. The Tequesta Indians fished, hunted, and gathered the fruit and roots of plants for food, but did not practice any form of agriculture. They buried the small bones of the deceased with the rest of the body, and put the larger bones in a box for the village people to see. The Tequesta are credited with making the [[Miami Circle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historymiami.org/visit/miami-circle/|title=Miami Circle to Brickell Avenue \u2013 From Native to NOW! \u2013 HistoryMiami Museum|website=www.historymiami.org}}</ref>\n\n===Founding of Broward===\nAlthough the area has been settled since about 1400 B.C., Broward County was founded on April 30, 1915.<ref name=\"Greater Fort Lauderdale\">{{cite web | title=broward county history | website=Greater Fort Lauderdale | url=http://www.sunny.org/history/ | accessdate=2015-10-02}}</ref> It was intended to be named Everglades County, but then-[[Speaker of the Florida House of Representatives]] [[Ion Farris]] amended the bill that established the county to name it in honor of [[Napoleon Bonaparte Broward]], governor of Florida from 1905 to 1909.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reese|first=J. H|title=Carved from Dade County|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dI4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XOoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3650,4363848&dq=ion-farris|accessdate=September 8, 2010|newspaper=[[The Miami News|The Weekly Miami Metropolis]]|date=May 16, 1913|location=[[Miami, Florida|Miami]], Florida|page=7}}</ref> Throughout his term as governor, Broward championed Everglades drainage and was remembered for his campaign to turn the Everglades into \u201cuseful land\u201d. This opened up much of today's urban Broward County for development, first as agricultural land and later as residential. A year before Broward became governor, Dania became the first incorporated community of what is now Broward County, followed by Pompano in 1908, and Fort Lauderdale in 1911.\n\nIn 1915, [[Palm Beach County]] and [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Dade County]] contributed nearly equal portions of land to create Broward County.<ref name=\"Greater Fort Lauderdale\" /> Dixie Highway was also completed through Broward County in 1915. In 1916, the settlement of \"Zona\" was renamed [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] in recognition of Robert P. Davie, a land developer who purchased a great deal of reclaimed Everglades land.\n\nBroward County began a huge development boom after its incorporation, with the first \"tourist hotel\", in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], opening in 1919. A year later, developers began dredging wetlands in the county to create island communities.<ref name=\"Greater Fort Lauderdale\" />\n\n===Land boom and rapid growth===\n1925 was considered the peak of the Florida land boom with Davie, [[Deerfield, Florida|Deerfield]], [[Oakland Park, Florida|Floranada]], and [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]] all being incorporated. By 1925, the boom was considered to have reached its peak, but the [[1926 Miami hurricane]] caused economic depression in the county.<ref name=\"Greater Fort Lauderdale\" />  In 1926, the [[Hollywood Seminole Indian Reservation]] (formerly \"Dania Reservation\") was opened. In 1927, [[Lauderdale-by-the-Sea, Florida|Lauderdale-by-the-Sea]] was incorporated. In 1928, the Bay Mabel Harbor (now the [[Port Everglades]] channel) was opened. In 1929, Merle Fogg Airport (now site of [[Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport]]) was dedicated. In 1939, [[Hillsboro Beach, Florida|Hillsboro Beach]] was incorporated. [[Gulfstream Park]] also opened in [[Hallandale Beach, Florida|Hallandale]] in 1939.\n\nThe county saw another population and development boom [[Post\u2013World War II baby boom|post]]-[[World War II]] when the transformation from agricultural to urbanized residential area began. In 1947, Pompano merged with beach area to form the present day [[Pompano Beach, Florida|City of Pompano Beach]].\n\nThere was another boom between the 1950s and the late 1960s. In 1953, [[Plantation, Florida|Plantation]], [[Lazy Lake, Florida|Lazy Lake]], and [[Fern Crest Village, Florida|Fern Crest Village]] were incorporated. In 1955, [[Margate, Florida|Margate]] and [[Miramar, Florida|Miramar]] were incorporated. In 1956, [[Lighthouse Point, Florida|Lighthouse Point]] was incorporated and the [[Florida Turnpike]] was completed through Broward County. In 1957, [[Pembroke Park, Florida|Pembroke Park]] was incorporated. In 1959, [[Cooper City, Florida|Cooper City]], [[Lauderhill, Florida|Lauderhill]], and [[Sea Ranch Lakes, Florida|Sea Ranch Lakes]] were incorporated.\n\nIn 1946 Dr. [[Von D. Mizell]] and black business owners petitioned the County Commission to make a county beach available to African Americans; at the time the beaches in Broward County, as elsewhere in Florida, were for whites only. Eight years later a beach, today [[Dr. Von D. Mizell-Eula Johnson State Park]], in [[Dania Beach]], was made available, but there was no road to it until 1965. In the meantime, Mizell and [[Eula Johnson]], with supporters, deliberately violated the law on July 4, 1961, by wading into the water on Ft. Lauderdale beach. The legal process set in motion by this incident resulted in the desegregation of Broward County beaches in 1962.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Wade in the Water\n|first=Robert\n|last=Beatty\n|date=April 10, 2008\n|newspaper=[[South Florida Times]]\n|url=http://www.sfltimes.com/uncategorized/wade-in-the-water\n|access-date=August 26, 2019\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826110044/http://www.sfltimes.com/uncategorized/wade-in-the-water\n|archive-date=August 26, 2019\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, the [[Pembroke Pines, Florida|City of Pembroke Pines]] was incorporated. This same year marked the opening of [[Broward College]] (then Broward Community College).\n\nIn 1961, [[Lauderdale Lakes, Florida|Lauderdale Lakes]] and [[Sunrise, Florida|Sunrise]] were incorporated. In 1963, the cities of [[Coral Springs, Florida|Coral Springs]], [[North Lauderdale, Florida|North Lauderdale]], [[Parkland, Florida|Parkland]], and [[Tamarac, Florida|Tamarac]] were all incorporated. In 1967, [[Coconut Creek, Florida|Coconut Creek]] was incorporated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunny.org/beaches-and-beyond/neighorhoods/broward-county-history/|title=Broward County History &#124; See The Historical Timeline from 1400 BC|website=www.sunny.org}}</ref>\n\nThe effects of a national recession hit the county in 1974 and the population growth finally slowed. This is from a peak growth percentage change of 297.9% which saw the population of Broward grow from 83,933 as of [[1950 United States Census|1950]] to 333,946 in [[1960 United States Census|1960]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/fl190090.txt</ref> The population subsequently experienced an 85.7% population growth which brought the population to a total of 620,100 in [[1970 United States Census|1970]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Recent history===\nThe structure of the Broward County government was signed into law in 1975 with the passage of the Broward County charter.<ref name=\"Greater Fort Lauderdale\" /> In the same year, the [[Seminole Tribe of Florida]] incorporated as a governing entity and began organizing cigarette sales, bingo and land leases that will bring millions of dollars in annual revenue in later years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stofinc.com/our-organization/|title=Our Organization|date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> In 1976, [[Interstate 95]] was completed through Broward County.\n\nOn January 19, 1977, snow fell in South Florida for the first time in recorded history. Snow was seen across all of South Florida as far south as [[Homestead, Florida|Homestead]] and even on Miami Beach. Snow was officially reported by weather observers in West Palm Beach, LaBelle, Hollywood, and Royal Palm Ranger Station in deep South Miami-Dade County.<ref>https://www.weather.gov/media/mfl/news/SnowArticleSouthFlorida40th.pdf</ref>\n\nIn the year 1980, the [[US census]] reported over 1 million people living in Broward County.\n\nOn August 24, 1992, [[Hurricane Andrew]] passed through Miami-Dade county causing $100 million in damage in Broward County and leaving at least a dozen residents homeless as a result of storm related fires. Broward becomes a base of operations to shuttle supplies to neighbors in devastated Dade County which suffered the brunt of the storm and caused over $25 billion in damage. Hurricane Andrew caused a massive exodus from South Dade to Broward County filling Pembroke Pines and other Broward communities with tens of thousands of transplanted families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/1992andrew.html|title=TPC NHC HURRICANE ANDREW|website=www.nhc.noaa.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2000, US census reported a total population 1,623,018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U. S. Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder.census.gov|access-date=2018-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table|archive-date=2011-07-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The town of [[Southwest Ranches, Florida|South West Ranches]] was incorporated this year.\n\nOn March 1, 2005, [[West Park, Florida|West Park]] became Broward County's 31st municipality to be incorporated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.cityofwestpark.net/residents/about-west-park |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113031332/https://web.cityofwestpark.net/residents/about-west-park |archive-date=2018-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2005, [[Hurricane Wilma]] hit [[South Florida]] leaving the entire area damaged and causing almost universal power outages. Wilma was the most damaging storm in Broward County since [[Hurricane King]] in 1950. Broward experienced wind speeds between 80 and 100&nbsp;mph (130 and 160&nbsp;km/h) which endured for about five hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/mfl/wilma|title=Wilma|first=NOAA|last=US Department of Commerce|website=www.weather.gov}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Fort Lauderdale-harbor.jpg|1000px|alt=Fort Lauderdale harbor|The [[Fort Lauderdale]] harbor and skyline}}\n\n==Geography==\n{{climate chart\n| Broward County, FL<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usa.com/broward-county-fl-weather.htm#HistoricalTemperature|title=Broward County, FL Weather - USA.com\u2122|website=www.usa.com}}</ref>\n|56.2|75|2.7\n|57.9|77.2|2.6\n|60.9|79.7|3.7\n|64.1|83.3|2.9\n|68.7|87|4.3\n|72.9|89.6|8.6\n|74|91.2|6.9\n|74.4|91.3|7.7\n|73.9|89.5|7.9\n|70.2|85.8|5.1\n|64.6|80.9|3.4\n|59.1|76.6|2.2\n|units = imperial\n|float = right\n|clear = both }}According to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has an area of {{convert|1323|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|1210|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|113|sqmi}} (8.5%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020527061848/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|archive-date=May 27, 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBroward County has an average elevation of six feet (1.8 m) above sea level. It is rather new geologically and at the eastern edge of the [[Florida Platform]], a [[carbonate]] plateau created millions of years ago. Broward County is composed of [[Oolite]] [[limestone]] while western Broward is composed mostly of [[Bryozoa]].<ref>[http://www.fiu.edu/~whitmand/Courses/Fl_geo_notes.html Notes on Florida Geography, Florida International University]</ref> Broward is among the last areas of Florida to be created and populated with fauna and flora, mostly in the [[Pleistocene]].\n\nOf developable land in Broward County, approximately {{convert|471|sqmi|1}}, the majority is built upon, as the urban area is bordered by the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to the east and the Everglades Wildlife Management Area to the west. Within developable land, Broward County has a population density of 3,740 per square mile (1,444 per square kilometer).\n\nBroward approved the construction of [[Osborne Reef]], an [[artificial reef]] made of tires off the Fort Lauderdale beach, but it has proven an environmental disaster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/17189132 |title=Tire reef off Florida proves a disaster - U.S. news - Environment - NBC News |publisher=NBC News |date=February 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]] - north\n* [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] - south\n* [[Collier County, Florida|Collier County]] - west\n* [[Hendry County, Florida|Hendry County]] - northwest\n\n{{wide image|Broward County Sunset Aerial Shot.jpg|750px|An aerial shot of the sunset looking Westward in Broward County, FL. The Everglades is shown in the background and beyond that is [[Collier County, Florida|Collier County]].}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 5135\n|1930= 20094\n|1940= 39794\n|1950= 83933\n|1960= 333946\n|1970= 620100\n|1980= 1018200\n|1990= 1255488\n|2000= 1623018\n|2010= 1748066\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=1952778\n|estref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/browardcountyflorida/PST045218|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Broward County, Florida|website=www.census.gov}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 12, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/fl190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2015<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/table/PST120214/12011|title=US Census 2015 Estimate|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== 2015 5-Year American Community Survey ===\n[[File:Fort Lauderdale Skyline 7.jpg|thumb|right|City skyline, featuring [[Las Olas River House]] (center), [[110 Tower]] (far right), and [[Bank of America Plaza (Fort Lauderdale)|Bank of America Plaza]] (far left)]]\n[[File:Fort-lauderdale-man-of-steel.JPG|thumb|right|A yacht in Fort Lauderdale's harbor]]\n\n====Households and families====\nAs of the 2015 5-year ACS, Broward County had 1,843,152 people, 670,284 households, and 425,680 families. Of the 670,284 households in Broward County, 26.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 43% were married couples living together, 15.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.5% were non-families. 29.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.73 and the average family size was 3.43.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S1101&prodType=table|title=Households and Families 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025105/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S1101&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Age====\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 21.7% under the age of 18,  8.5% from 18 to 24, 26.9% from 25 to 44, 27.7% from 45 to 64, and 15.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 40 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.4 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 98.7 males.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S0101&prodType=table|title=Age and Sex 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022329/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S0101&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Race, ancestry and nationality====\nThe racial makeup of the county was 62.3% [[White Americans|White]], 17.1% [[Hispanic or Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] of any race), 12.2% [[African Americans|Black or African American]], 5.07% [[Asian Americans|Asian]], 2.20% from [[Multiracial Americans|two or more races]], 0.66% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], 0.16% [[Pacific Islands Americans|Pacific Islander]], and 0.20% from some other race. The racial makeup of the total Hispanic and Latino population in Broward County was: 65.8% [[White Hispanic and Latino Americans|White]], 5.90% Native American, 2.06% [[Black Hispanic and Latino Americans|Black or African American]], 0.33% [[Asian Hispanic and Latino Americans|Asian]], 0.86% Pacific Islander, 26.23% were some other race and 4.57% were from two or more races.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B03002&prodType=table|title=Hispanic or Latino Origin By Race 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107030025/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B03002&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2015, with relation to ancestry (excluding the various Hispanic and Latino ancestries), 7.38% were [[Italian Americans|Italian]], 7.70% American, 6.44% [[German Americans|German]], 6.54% [[Irish Americans|Irish]], 3.8% [[English Americans|English]], 2.6% [[Polish Americans|Polish]] and 2.2% [[Russian Americans|Russian]] ancestry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=bkmk|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U. S. Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder.census.gov|access-date=2019-07-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815134909/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=bkmk|archive-date=2014-08-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Also, among [[West Indian Americans|West Indians]], 6.33% were [[Haitian Americans|Haitian]] and 5.96% were [[Jamaican Americans|Jamaican]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B04006&prodType=table|title=People Reporting Ancestry 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718111231/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B04006&prodType=table|archive-date=2018-07-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2015, 32.2% of the county's population was foreign born, with 18.14% being naturalized American citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B05001&prodType=table|title=Nativity and Citizenship Status in the United States 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025836/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B05001&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> Of foreign born residents, 78.9% were born in Latin America, 7.88% were born in Europe, 8.52% born in Asia, 3.11% in North America, 1.34% born in Africa and 0.15 were born in Oceania.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B05006&prodType=table|title=Place of Birth for the Foreign-Born Population in the United States Universe: Foreign-born excluding population born at sea 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003649/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B05006&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Income====\nAs of the 2015 5-year ACS, the median income for a household in the county was $51,968, and the median income for a family was $61,809.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S1901&prodType=table|title=Income in the Past 12 Months (In 2015 Inflation-Adjusted Dollars) 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218064406/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_S1901&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-02-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> Of full-time workers, males had a median income of $46,372 versus $39,690 for females.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B19326&prodType=table|title=Median Income In the Past 12 Months (In 2015 Inflation-Adjusted Dollars) By Sex By Work Experience In the Past 12 months For The population 15 years and over with Income : 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055057/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B19326&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> The per capita income for the county was $28,381. About 11.2% of families and 14.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 19.9% of those under the age 18 and 12.6% of those aged 65 or over.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_DP03&prodType=table|title=Selected Economic Characteristics 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015605/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_DP03&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2010 Census===\n<u>U.S. Census Bureau 2010 Ethnic/Race Demographics:</u><ref name=brocodemo>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |title=Broward County: SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates |publisher=factfinder.census.gov |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234526/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=PDFbrocodemo>{{cite web |url=https://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/BBTN58April2012Update.pdf |title=Broward-by-the-Numbers (June 2011): Census 2010 - Early Results (Page 4) |publisher=www.broward.org |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151221092730/http://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/BBTN58April2012Update.pdf |archive-date=2015-12-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=brocoflodemo>{{cite web |url=http://data.ocala.com/census/florida/broward-county/011/ |title=Broward County Demographic Characteristics |publisher=ocala.com |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811063911/http://data.ocala.com/census/florida/broward-county/011/ |archive-date=2016-08-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[White (U.S. Census)|White (non-Hispanic)]] : 42.5% <small>(8.7% Irish, 8.2% Italian, 7.9% German, 5.0% English, 3.2% Polish, 2.7% Russian, 1.9% French, 1.0% Scottish, 0.8% Dutch, 0.8% Scotch-Irish, 0.8% Hungarian, 0.6% Swedish, 0.6% French Canadian, 0.5% Greek)</small><ref name=\"brocodemo\" />(63.1% when including [[White Hispanic]]s)\n* [[Black (U.S. Census)|Black (non-Hispanic)]] (26.7% when including [[Black Hispanic]]s): 17.7% <small>(12.8% [[West Indian]]/[[Afro-Caribbean American]] [5.7% Haitian, 5.3% Jamaican, 0.4% Trinidadian and Tobagonian, 0.4% [[Afro-Caribbean|Other or Unspecified West Indian]], 0.3% Bahamian, 0.2% [[British West Indian]], 0.1% Barbadian,] 0.8% [[Sub-Saharan Africa|Subsaharan African]])</small><ref name=brocodemo/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |title=Broward County, Florida FIRST ANCESTRY REPORTED Universe: Total population - 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates |publisher=factfinder.census.gov |accessdate=November 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234526/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race: 26.9% <small>(4.8% Cuban, 4.3% Puerto Rican, 3.8% Colombian, 1.7% Mexican, 1.6% Dominican, 1.4% Peruvian, 1.3% Venezuelan, 0.7% Ecuadoran, 0.7% Honduran, 0.6% Argentinean, 0.5% Nicaraguan, 0.5% Salvadoran)</small><ref name=brocoflodemo/><ref name=BCLaHi>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |title=Hispanic or Latino by Type: 2010 more information - 2010 Census Summary File 1 |publisher=factfinder.census.gov |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234526/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]]: 3.2% <small>(1.2% Indian [including [[Indo-Caribbean Americans|Indo-Caribbeans]]], 0.6% Chinese [including [[Chinese Caribbeans]]], 0.5% Other Asian, 0.4% Filipino, 0.3% Vietnamese, 0.1% Japanese, 0.1% Korean)</small><ref name=PDFbrocodemo/><ref name=brocoflodemo/>\n* [[Multiracial American|Two or more races]]: 2.9%\n* [[Native American (U.S. Census)|American Indian and Alaska Native]]: 0.3%\n* [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander]]: 0.1%\n* [[Race (United States Census)|Other Races]]: 3.7% <small>(0.7% Arab)</small><ref name=brocodemo/>\n\nIn 2010, 4.7% of the population considered themselves to be of only \"[[American people|American]]\" ancestry (regardless of race or ethnicity.)<ref name=brocodemo/>\n\n{{as of|2010}}, [[Haitian people|Haitians]] made up the largest population of [[immigrant]]s, with [[Jamaican people|Jamaicans]] coming in second, [[Colombian people|Colombians]] in third, followed by [[Cuban people|Cuban]] [[exile]]d [[refugee]]s in fourth place, then [[Peruvian people|Peruvians]], [[Venezuelan people|Venezuelans]], [[Brazilian people|Brazilians]], [[Dominican people (Dominican Republic)|Dominicans]], [[Canadians]], and [[Mexican people|Mexicans]] being the tenth highest group of [[expatriates]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-05-11/news/fl-census-foreign-born-20120510_1_foreign-born-first-haitian-baptist-church-large-haitian-population | title=Broward's foreign-born population soars | newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] | accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> The county also houses many British, French, German, and Spanish expatriates.\n\nThere were 810,388 households out of which 28.61% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.80% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.28% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.67% were non-families. 28.79% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.07% (3.31% male and 7.76% female) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.52 and the average family size was 3.14.<ref name=brocodemo/><ref name=BCage>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |title=Miami-Dade County: Age Groups and Sex: 2010 - 2010 Census Summary File 1 |publisher=factfinder.census.gov |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234526/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe age distribution is 22.4% under the age of 18, 8.4% from 18 to 24, 27.2% from 25 to 44, 27.7% from 45 to 64, and 14.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39.7 years. For every 100 females, there were 93.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.0 males.<ref name=BCage/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $51,694, and the median income for a family was $62,619. Males had a median income of $44,935 versus $36,813 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $28,631. About 9.1% of families and 12.3% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16.2% of those under age 18 and 12.2% of those aged 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF |title=Broward County, Florida: SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS - 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates |publisher=factfinder.census.gov |accessdate=November 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129082905/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, 30.9% of the county's population was [[foreign born]], with 49.2% being [[Naturalized citizen of the United States|naturalized American citizens]]. Of foreign born residents, 77.4% were born in [[Latin America]], 9.0% were born in [[Europe]], 8.4% born in [[Asia]], 3.5% in [[North America]], 1.6% born in [[Africa]], and 0.1% were born in [[Oceania]].<ref name=brocodemo/>\n\nAccording to the 2010 U.S. Census,<ref name=\"U.S. Census Bureau\">{{cite web|title=Census|url=https://census.gov/|accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> Broward County is the 9th largest county with same sex households. As of the 2010 Census, there were 9,125 same sex households out of a total of 686,047 households (1.33%).<ref name=\"U.S. Census Bureau\"/>\n\n===2000 Census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 1,623,018 people, 654,445 households, and 411,645 families residing in the county. The [[population density]] was 1,346 people per square mile (520/km\u00b2). There were 741,043 housing units at an average density of 615 per square&nbsp;mile (237/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the county was 70.57% [[Race (United States Census)|White]] (58% were Non-Hispanic),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.muninetguide.com/states/florida/Broward.php |title=Demographics of Broward County, FL |publisher=MuniNetGuide.com |accessdate=December 19, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071111155654/http://www.muninetguide.com/states/florida/Broward.php |archive-date=2007-11-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 20.54% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.24% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 2.25% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.06% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 3.00% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 3.35% from two or more races. 16.74% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nIn 2000, with relation to [[ancestry]] (excluding the various [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] and [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] ancestries), 9.4% were [[Italians|Italian]], 7.4% [[United States|American]], 6.8% [[Germans|German]], 6.7% [[Irish people|Irish]], and 4% [[English people|English]] ancestry. Also, among [[West Indian]]s, 5.99% were [[Haitian people|Haitian]] and were 5.91% [[Jamaican people|Jamaican]].<ref name=CDbroco>{{cite web |url=http://www.city-data.com/county/Broward_County-FL.html |title=Broward County, FL Detailed Profile |publisher=city-data.com |accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> Broward was the only county in the nation outside the [[Northeastern U.S.|Northeast]] in which [[Italian-Americans]] formed the largest ethnic group in 2000. They are concentrated mainly in the [[Pompano Beach]] area.<ref name=CDbroco/>\n\nThere were 654,445 households out of which 29.30% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.1% were non-families. 29.6% of all households were made up of individuals and % had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 3.07.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 23.6% under the age of 18, 7.2% from 18 to 24, 31.4% from 25 to 44, 21.7% from 45 to 64, and 16.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 38 years. For every 100 females, there were 93.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $41,691, and the median income for a family was $50,531. Males had a median income of $36,741 versus $28,529 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $23,170. About 8.7% of families and 11.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 15.3% of those under age 18 and 10.0% of those age 65 or over.\n\nAs of 2005, Broward County led the nation's metropolitan areas in new [[AIDS]] diagnoses, with a reported rate 58.4 new AIDS diagnoses per 100,000 people. County officials think the numbers may stem from a new and successful [[HIV]] testing campaign that has resulted in many people being diagnosed with AIDS at the same time they've been diagnosed with HIV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebody.com/updates/2005-11-23.html |title=What's New at The Body, November 23, 2005 |publisher=Thebody.com |date= |accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> Without the implementation of the new testing campaign, the reported numbers of new diagnoses would have probably been lower.\n\n===Languages===\n{{as of|2010}}, 63.44% of all residents spoke [[English language|English]] as their [[first language]], while 22.22% spoke [[Spanish language|Spanish]], 5.42% [[French-based creole languages|French Creole]] (mostly [[Haitian Creole]]), 1.48% [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], 1.41% [[French language|French]], and 0.59% of the population spoke [[Italian language|Italian]] as their [[mother language]]. In total, 36.56% of the population spoke languages other than English as their [[primary language]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mla.org/map_data_results&state_id=12&county_id=11&mode=geographic&zip=&place_id=&cty_id=&ll=&a=&ea=&order=r | title=Modern Language Association Data Center Results, Broward County, Florida | publisher=Modern Language Association | accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> Since many [[immigrant]]s are coming from the [[Anglophone Caribbean]], where English is spoken, the change is not as fast as the rate of immigration would suggest.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}\n\n==Law, government, and politics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align = right style=\"margin:auto; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Broward County Mayors'''\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! Name\n! Start of Term\n! End of Term\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|Mark Bogen<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fl-ne-broward-new-mayor-20181126-story.html|title=Mark Bogen chosen as new Broward mayor|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=August 3, 2019|publisher=Sun Sentinel}}</ref>\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 2018\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 2019\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|Beam Furr<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-sb-broward-county-mayor-furr-20171127-story.html|title=Broward County gets new mayor after outgoing leader touts accomplishments|date=November 28, 2017|accessdate=August 3, 2019|publisher=Sun Sentinel}}</ref>\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 2017\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 2018\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|[[Barbara Sharief]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 17, 2016\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 17, 2017\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|[[Martin David Kiar|Marty Kiar]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 17, 2015\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 17, 2016\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|[[Tim M. Ryan|Tim Ryan]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 18, 2014\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 17, 2015\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0ff;\"|[[Barbara Sharief]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 19, 2013\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff3f3;\"|Nov. 18, 2014\n|}\nThe Broward County [[Charter]] provides for a separation between the legislative and administrative functions of government. The Board of County Commissioners is the legislative branch of Broward County Government. The County Commission is composed of nine members elected by district. Each Commissioner must be a resident of the district for which he or she seeks election. Each year the Commission elects a [[mayor]] and [[vice mayor]]. The mayor's functions include serving as presiding officer, and as the county's official representative. The Commission appoints the County Administrator, County Attorney and County Auditor. The Commission also appoints numerous advisory and regulatory boards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.broward.org/Charter/Documents/BC-Charter.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204211042/https://www.broward.org/Charter/Documents/BC-Charter.pdf |archive-date=2020-02-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe County Commission meets in formal session the first four Tuesdays of each month at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. in Room 422 of the Broward County Governmental Center. Over 507,000 cable subscribers in Broward County have access to [[Government-access television]] (GATV) coverage of Commission meetings, which are broadcast live beginning at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. each Tuesday, and rebroadcast at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. the following Friday. Meetings can also be viewed via webcasting at www.broward.org.\n\n===Politics===\n\n====Overview====\nBroward County has voted for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate in most of the presidential elections in the past four decades, and has gone Democratic in every election since 1992. It voted twice for [[Ronald Reagan]] (1980, 1984) and once for [[George H. W. Bush]] (1988). From 1916 to 1972 it voted Democratic six times and Republican in nine elections. In 2008 and 2012 approximately 67.07% of the electorate voted for Democrat [[Barack Obama]]. In 2016, Democrat [[Hillary Clinton]] won 66.08% of the vote.\n\n====Election history====\nFrom 1948 to 1988, the county went Republican in every election except for [[U.S. presidential election, 1976|1976]]. In the [[U.S. presidential election, 1964|1964 presidential election]], the county supported [[Barry Goldwater]] by a 56-44 margin even as he lost in a landslide nationwide, and in the [[U.S. presidential election, 1972|1972 presidential election]], Broward County voters strongly backed [[Richard Nixon]] over [[George McGovern]]. But since 1992, Broward County has supported the Democratic [[presidential nominee]] by increasing majorities. It is now the most reliably Democratic county in the state,<ref name=\"Broward Power\">[http://www.sptimes.com/2002/04/28/news_pf/State/Broward_Power.shtml State:Broward Power]. [[St. Petersburg Times]]. Retrieved November 14, 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/elections/orl-elections-nationalmap-ap,0,5015729.htmlpage 2008 General Election Results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011112119/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/elections/orl-elections-nationalmap-ap,0,5015729.htmlpage |date=2012-10-11 }}. [[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]]. Retrieved November 11, 2008.</ref> with the exception of the much less populous and majority [[African American]] [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden County]] in North Florida. This change in voting tendencies can be attributed to the large [[human migration|migrations]] of middle and upper-class [[snowbird (people)|snowbirds and transplants]] from more [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] states, a growing [[LGBT]] community, liberal positions on social issues such as abortion and gun control, and [[U.S. citizenship#Naturalization|naturalized U.S. citizens]] born in places such as [[Latin America]], the [[Caribbean]], [[Canada]], [[Europe]], and [[Asia]].\n\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Previous gubernatorial elections results'''\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|31.30% ''222,012 (DeSantis)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''67.98%''' ''482,152 (Gillum)''\n|align=\"center\" |0.68% ''5,015''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|29.52% ''138,394 (Scott/Incumbent)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''68.02%''' ''318,950 (Crist)''\n|align=\"center\" |2.46% ''11,549''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|33.40% ''140,445 (Scott)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''64.59%''' ''271,606 (Sink)''\n|align=\"center\" |2.01% ''8,480''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|35.09% ''143,043 (Crist)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''62.81%''' ''256,072 (Davis)''\n|align=\"center\" |2.10% ''8,558''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2002|2002]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|40.02% ''175,756 (Bush/Incumbent)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''59.05%''' ''259,370 (McBride)''\n|align=\"center\" |0.93% ''4,076''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 1998|1998]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|37.93% ''137,494 (Bush)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''62.07%''' ''225,010 (McKay)''\n|align=\"center\" |0.00% ''8  ''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Florida gubernatorial election, 1994|1994]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|34.61% ''138,333 (Bush)''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''65.39%''' ''261,368 (Chiles/Incumbent)''\n|align=\"center\" |0.00% ''11  ''\n|}\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:1em 0 1em 1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Broward County vote<br /> by party in presidential elections'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! Others\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|31.16% ''260,951''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''66.08%''' ''553,320''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.76% ''23,117''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|32.23% ''244,101''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''67.12%''' ''508,312''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; backgroun