ach, but the airport is not in the city limits--> Other companies with headquarters in unincorporated areas include [[Locair]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090507185056/http://www.locair.net/pages/contact.htm Contact Us].\" [[Locair]]. Retrieved on June 19, 2010. \"Locair, Inc. 268 SW 33rd St. Fort Lauderdale, FL 33315\"</ref>\n\n[[Spirit Airlines]] has its headquarters in [[Miramar, Florida|Miramar]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nWhen [[Chalk's International Airlines]] existed, its headquarters was on the grounds of the airport in an unincorporated area.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20040331100714/http://www.flychalks.com/ Administration].\" [[Chalk's International Airlines]]. March 31, 2004. Retrieved on December 17, 2011. \"Chalk\u2019s International Airlines 704 SW 34th Street Ft Lauderdale, Fl. 33315\"</ref> When [[Bimini Island Air]] existed, its headquarters were in an unincorporated area.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.flybia.com/contactus.asp Contact Us].\" Bimini Island Air. Retrieved on July 12, 2011. \"Bimini Island Air, Inc./Ltd. 3000 NW 59 Street Fort Lauderdale, FL 33309\"</ref>\n\n==Education==\n===Primary and secondary schools===\n[[File:BCC South Campus - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Broward College South Campus administration building]]\n[[Broward County Schools]] has the [[List of the largest school districts in the United States by enrollment|sixth largest]] [[Broward County Public Schools|school district]] in the country and the second largest in the state after the [[Miami-Dade County Public Schools|Miami-Dade district]].\n\n===Regionally accredited colleges and universities===\n* [[Broward College]]\n* [[Florida Atlantic University]]  Campus Locations - Main Campus in Palm Beach County\n* [[Nova Southeastern University]]\n* [[Keiser University]]\n\n===Other adult education providers===\n* [[DeVry University]]\n* [[University of Phoenix]]\n* [[The Art Institute of Fort Lauderdale]]\n*Florida Career College\n*[[Brown Mackie College]]\n*[[Atlantic Technical Center and Technical High School]]\n*[[McFatter Technical College and Technical High School]]\n*[[Sheridan Technical College and High School|Sheridan Technical College and Technical High School]]\n\n===Public libraries===\nThe [[Broward County Library]] is one of the largest public library systems in the country, comprising 38 branch locations. There are also five municipal public libraries in the county that are not part of the Broward County Library system: Ethel M. Gordon Oakland Park Library, Lighthouse Point Library, Helen B. Hoffman Plantation Library, and Parkland Public Library.\n\n====Library Resources====\nBroward county libraries provide endless amount of resources to the public. For high-schoolers looking to prepare themselves for college, the library offers college readiness & [https://www.broward.org/Library/Pages/SATACTProgram.aspx SAT/ACT prep courses]. For adults looking to learn computer skills, [https://www.broward.org/Library/Pages/SATACTProgram.aspx adult computer classes] are also offered. These resources are free of cost, therefore, all it takes is registering to participate. In addition to the many resources offered at the library, bus passes are also made available at most Broward County libraries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broward.org:443/BCT/Pages/Outlets.aspx|title=Broward County Transit|website=www.broward.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> If you want to enjoy some of these resources, you can simply download the app to utilize them on the go. There are nine apps available for download: Broward County Library (BCL WoW), Freegal Music, Hoopla, Overdrive, Libby, Axis 360, RBdigital Magazines, Rosetta Stone, and Brainfuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broward.org:443/Library/Pages/MobileApps.aspx|title=Library|website=www.broward.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Most of these apps you can easily gain access to by simply using your library card number.\n\n==Sites of interest==\n[[File:Bonnet House Museum & Gardens (Fort Lauderdale, Florida) 003.jpg|thumb|[[Bonnet House|Bonnet House Museum & Gardens]], Fort Lauderdale]]\n[[File:Stranahan House 1.jpg|thumb|Stranahan House, Fort Lauderdale]]\n\n===Museums and historical collections===\n{{also|List of museums in Broward County, Florida}}\n*[[African-American Research Library and Cultural Center]], Fort Lauderdale\n*[[Bonnet House|Bonnet House Museum & Gardens]], Fort Lauderdale\n*[[Coral Springs Museum of Art]], Coral Springs\n*Fort Lauderdale Antique Car Museum, Fort Lauderdale<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.antiquecarmuseum.net/|title=Ft. Lauderdale Antique Car Museum|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2019|website=antiquecarmuseum.net|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Fort Lauderdale History Center]], Fort Lauderdale\n*[[Link Trainer Building|Naval Air Station Fort Lauderdale Museum]], Fort Lauderdale\n*[[Museum of Art Fort Lauderdale|NSU Art Museum]], Fort Lauderdale\n*Plantation Historical Museum, Plantation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.plantation.org/Museum/|title=Plantation Historical MUseum|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2019|website=plantation.org|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Stranahan House]], Fort Lauderdale\n*The [[International Game Fish Association]], including the Fishing Hall of Fame & Museum, [[Dania Beach]]\n*The [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]], [[Fort Lauderdale]]\n*The [[Museum of Discovery and Science]], Fort Lauderdale\n*Wiener Museum of Decorative Arts, Dania Beach<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wmoda.com/|title=Wiener Museum of Decorative Arts|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2019|website=wmoda.com|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108093855/http://wmoda.com/|archive-date=November 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Young at Art Museum]], Davie\n\n===Nature and wildlife areas===\n[[File:Butterfly World, Florida.jpg|thumb|Butterfly World, Coconut Creek]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20171108035555/http://www.broward.org/parks/westlakepark/pages/annekolbnaturecenter.aspx Anne Kolb Nature Center], Hollywood\n*[[Butterfly World]], a botanical sanctuary in [[Coconut Creek]]\n* Fern Forest Nature Center, Coconut Creek\n* [[Flamingo Gardens]], a botanical garden and wildlife sanctuary\n*Secret Woods Nature Center, Dania Beach\n*Sawgrass Recreation Park\n*The [[Everglades]] parks, which have multiple entrances in Broward County\n\n===Other areas and attractions===\n[[File:Hollywood Beach boardwalk - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Hollywood Beach Boardwalk]]\n* Beach Place, a strip of stores, restaurants, and bars across the street from the beach along the Atlantic coast, in Ft. Lauderdale\n* Broward Center for the Performing Arts\n* Hollywood Broadwalk\n*Florida Grand Opera\n*[[Fort Lauderdale Swap Shop]] (colloquially known to locals as simply the Swap Shop)\n*[[Sawgrass Mills]], a large outlet shopping mall in [[Sunrise, Florida|Sunrise]]\n*The [[BB&T Center (Sunrise)|BB&T Center]] in Sunrise, where the [[NHL]]'s [[Florida Panthers]] play their games\n* The [[Festival Flea Market Mall]] in [[Pompano Beach]], America's largest indoor flea market\n*[[Riverwalk (Fort Lauderdale)]]\n\nAdditionally, with 23 miles of beach, Broward County is a popular destination for scuba diving, snorkeling, and droves of young [[Spring break]] tourists from around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Florida Beach Dive Sites|url=http://sinkfloridasink.com/south-florida-dive-sites/south-florida-beach-dives/|website=Sink, Florida, Sink!|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=More spring tourists filling hotels|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/tourism/fl-spring-travel-2015-20150320-story.html|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|accessdate=21 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506105306/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/tourism/fl-spring-travel-2015-20150320-story.html|archive-date=6 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n===Airports===\n[[File:Fort Lauderdale, Florida - FLL from airplane.jpg|thumb|[[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport]]]]\n[[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport]] serves as the primary airport of the Broward County area. The airport is bounded by the cities [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]] and [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]],<ref name=\"Zoning Map\"/><!--The airport is between parts of Dania Beach, but the airport is not in the city limits--> three miles (5&nbsp;km) southwest of downtown Fort Lauderdale and {{convert|21|mi|abbr=on}} north of Miami. The airport is near cruise line terminals at [[Port Everglades]] and is popular among tourists bound for the [[Caribbean]]. Since the late 1990s, FLL has become an intercontinental gateway, although [[Miami International Airport]] still handles most long-haul flights. FLL is ranked as the 19th busiest airport (in terms of passenger traffic) in the United States, as well as the nation's 14th busiest international air gateway and one of the world's 50 busiest airports. FLL is classified by the [[US Federal Aviation Administration]] as a \"major hub\" facility serving commercial air traffic. In 2017 the airport processed 32,511,053 passengers<ref name=\"ACI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.broward.org/Airport/About/Documents/Monthlystatsdecember2016.pdf |title=TOTAL PASSENGERS (ARRIVING + DEPARTING) \u2013 Monthly Stats |publisher=broward.org |date=December 2016 |accessdate=2017-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212092748/http://www.broward.org/Airport/About/Documents/Monthlystatsdecember2016.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (11.3% more than 2016) including 7,183,275 international passengers (18.6% more than 2016).\n\n* [[North Perry Airport]]\n* [[Fort Lauderdale Executive Airport]]\n* [[Pompano Beach Airpark]]\n*Downtown Fort Lauderdale Heliport\n[[File:BCTBus.jpg|right|thumb|A Broward County Transit bus in the current \"Breeze\" livery.]]\n\n===Public transportation===\n* [[Broward County Transit]]\n* [[Tri-Rail]]\n* [[Sun Trolley]]\n\n===Major expressways===\n[[File:Lauderdale from tri rail.jpg|thumb|[[Interstate 95 in Florida|Interstate 95]] as it passes through Fort Lauderdale. The city's skyline can be seen in the background.]]\n* [[File:I-95.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 95 in Florida|Interstate 95]]\n* [[File:I-75.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 75 in Florida|Interstate 75]]\n* [[File:I-595.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 595 (Florida)|Interstate 595]] (Port Everglades Expressway)\n* [[File:Florida's Turnpike shield.svg|25px]] [[Florida's Turnpike]] (SR 91)\n*[[File:Florida's Turnpike shield.svg|25px]] [[Homestead Extension of Florida's Turnpike|Homestead Extension]] (SR 821)\n* [[File:Toll Florida 869.svg|24px]] [[Florida State Road 869|State Road 869]] (Sawgrass Expressway)\n\n===Railroads===\n*[[Amtrak]], [[Tri-Rail]] and [[Virgin Trains USA]] run through Broward.\n\n===Street grid===\nA [[street grid]] stretches throughout Broward County. Most of this grid is loosely based on three primary eastern municipalities, (from South to North) Hollywood, Fort Lauderdale, and Pompano Beach. Deerfield Beach\u2014another primary eastern municipality\u2014has its own street grid, as do two smaller municipalities\u2014Dania and Hallandale.\n\n===Greenways System===\nConstruction is underway on a network of recreational trails to connect cities and points of interest in the county.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/broward/sfl-interstate-595-greenway-b062509,0,3474616.story |title=Topic Galleries - South Florida |publisher=Sun-sentinel.com |accessdate=August 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629070433/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/broward/sfl-interstate-595-greenway-b062509%2C0%2C3474616.story |archivedate=June 29, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broward.org/greenways/ |title=Welcome To Broward County Greenways |publisher=Broward.org |date= |accessdate=August 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925042551/http://www.broward.org/greenways/ |archive-date=September 25, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"First leg of bike trail open along I-595\">{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/fl-i-595-bike-trail-20100818,0,5166788.story |title=Topic Galleries |publisher=OrlandoSentinel.com |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Map of Broward County Florida.svg|550px|right|thumb|Map of the municipalities (colored areas) and unincorporated communities (grey areas) of Broward County]]\n\n===Municipalities===\nMunicipality populations are based on the 2015 5-year American Community Survey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |title=See \"Population and Housing Occupancy Status: 2010 - Florida County -- County Subdivision and Place\" |work=2010 Census |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B01003&prodType=table|title=Total Population 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917013350/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_15_5YR_B01003&prodType=table|archive-date=2017-09-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!#\n!Incorporated community\n!Designation\n!Date incorporated\n!Population\n|-\n| 2 || [[Coconut Creek, Florida|Coconut Creek]] || City || {{dts|1967|2|20}} || 56,816\n|-\n| 26 || [[Cooper City, Florida|Cooper City]] || City || {{dts|1959|6|20}} || 33,382\n|-\n| 4 || [[Coral Springs, Florida|Coral Springs]] || City || {{dts|1963|7|10}} || 126,673\n